{
  "doc_id": "5438",
  "text": "The antiviral efficacy factor AVF(I i , I s ) = (1 -AVE i )* (1 -AVE s ) represents the potential reduction in infectiousness of an infected individual (denoted by AVE i ) induced by antiviral treatment, and the reduction in susceptibility of a susceptible individual (denoted by AVE s ) induced by antiviral prophylaxis. When no antiviral intervention was administrated the values of both AVE i and AVE s were assumed to be 0, indicating no reduction in infectiousness or susceptibility. However, when antiviral treatment was being applied to the infectious individual the value of AVE i was set at 0.66, capturing a reduction in infectiousness by factor of 66% [CITATION_1] . Similarly, when the susceptible individual was undergoing antiviral prophylaxis the value of AVE s was set to 0.85 indicating a reduction in susceptibility by a factor of 85% [CITATION_2] . This estimate is higher than most previous modelling studies, which assume an AVE of 30% (e.g. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ). This common assumption appears to stem from an estimate made in [CITATION_6] based on 1998-1999 trial data. Our higher value is based on a more comprehensive estimation process reported in [CITATION_7] , which also incorporated an data from an additional study performed in 2000-2001 [CITATION_8] . It is also in line with estimates of 64%-89% reported in [CITATION_9] .",
